<h4>
        shell itself!<!-- #$loop:item['xar_title']# -->
               </h4>
<!-- show changelog -->
<!-- end changelog -->
           <span class="xar-sub">
Posted by:                     Anonymous Coward
 on                 November 02, 2005 01:44 PM</span>
       </div>
       <div class="xar-accent xar-cm-comment">

                 
            
              I'm surprised how often people ignore the utility of shell itself.  Four builtin's come to mind as being extremely useful: alias, pushd, popd, and dirs.  alias is obvious.  It's your bookmark/shortcut utility.  Need to bookmark a directory?<blockquote> <div>&lt;tt&gt;$ echo 'alias dir1=&quot;pushd&lt;nobr&gt; &lt;wbr&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;/path/to/interesting/dir&quot;' &gt;&gt; ~/.bash_bookmarks<br>$ . ~/.bash_bookmarks<br>$ pwd<br>/i/am/here<br>$ dir1<br>/path/to/interesting/dir&lt;nobr&gt; &lt;wbr&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;/i/am/here<br>$ pwd<br>/path/to/interesting/dir&lt;/tt&gt;</div> </blockquote> <p>If you use a naming convention, such as prefixing the &quot;bookmark&quot; aliases with &quot;bk-&quot;, you can find your aliases by this command sequence:</p> <blockquote> <div>&lt;tt&gt;$ alias | grep &quot;bk-&quot;<br>alias bk-dir1=&quot;popd&lt;nobr&gt; &lt;wbr&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;/path/to/dir1&quot;<br>alias bk-dir2=&quot;popd&lt;nobr&gt; &lt;wbr&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;/path/to/dir2&quot;&lt;/tt&gt;</div> </blockquote> <p>In this example, you see the builtin command pushd being used.  What is this about?  It's a stackable &quot;cookie crumb trail&quot; for directory traversal.</p> <blockquote> <div>&lt;tt&gt;$ pushd&lt;nobr&gt; &lt;wbr&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;/path/i/want/to/go/to<br>/path/i/want/to/go/to&lt;nobr&gt; &lt;wbr&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;/path/i/was/last/in<br>$ dirs<br>/path/i/want/to/go/to&lt;nobr&gt; &lt;wbr&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;/path/i/was/last/in&lt;nobr&gt; &lt;wbr&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;/path1<br>$ pushd<br>/path/i/was/last/in&lt;nobr&gt; &lt;wbr&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;/path/i/want/to/go/to&lt;nobr&gt; &lt;wbr&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;/path1<br>$ popd<br>/path/i/want/to/go/to&lt;nobr&gt; &lt;wbr&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;/path1&lt;/tt&gt;</div> </blockquote> <p>You can bounce back and forth without having to type the path names.  The typical use pattern is to use &quot;pushd&quot; instead of your first &quot;cd&quot; command, use &quot;cd&quot; as you would normally do until you find the directory that's important to you, then use &quot;pushd&quot; to pop back to your original directory.</p><br />
<br />
<p>You can construct shell helper scripts relatively easily without ever having to use a compiler.</p><br />
<br />
<p>Help for shell builtins can be displayed with the &quot;help&quot; command (of course).</p> 

                <p>
                    <a href="http://www.linux.com/archive/?module=comments&amp;func=display&amp;cid=1149235" title="Permalink" rel="bookmark">
                       #
                   </a>
               </p>

       </div>

</div>

    <div class="xar-accent-outline xar-cm-comment">
    <div>
         <a name="1149245"></a>



