<h4>
        My 0.01 EUR/USD/GBP contribution.<!-- #$loop:item['xar_title']# -->
               </h4>
<!-- show changelog -->
<!-- end changelog -->
           <span class="xar-sub">
Posted by:                     Administrator
 on                 November 02, 2005 04:15 PM</span>
       </div>
       <div class="xar-accent xar-cm-comment">

                 
            
              No words about the text editor choice just like no words about your religion faith.<br><br />
I don't like dig as well as the old-fashioned nslookup because of the tight coupling with BIND. I prefer &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.dtek.chalmers.se/~d3august/xt/&quot; title=&quot;chalmers.se&quot;&gt;the independent host&lt;/a chalmers.se&gt; (read chap.3), an historical DNS tool.<br><br />
Finally, if I'd need to do some tests in TCP/UDP I'd choose either &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.securityfocus.com/tools/137&quot; title=&quot;securityfocus.com&quot;&gt;netcat&lt;/a securityfocus.com&gt; or &lt;a href=&quot;http://netcat.sourceforge.net/&quot; title=&quot;sourceforge.net&quot;&gt;GNU-netcat&lt;/a sourceforge.net&gt;.<br><br />
Of course there is no perefect choice in a absolute sense. I simply have found these tools more effective than the other ones. 

                <p>
                    <a href="http://www.linux.com/archive/?module=comments&amp;func=display&amp;cid=1149265" title="Permalink" rel="bookmark">
                       #
                   </a>
               </p>

       </div>

